1. PURPOSE AND SIGNATURE
String.prototype.codePointAt(pos) -> returns an integer representing the UTF-16 code point value at position pos in the string.

2. INPUT SEMANTICS
- pos: integer index into the string's UTF-16 code units. If omitted, defaults to 0.
- Non-integer or out-of-range values: numeric conversion applies; if pos < 0 or pos >= string.length -> undefined.

3. RETURN VALUES AND TYPES
- Returns a Number representing Unicode code point (0..0x10FFFF) for the code point starting at pos.
- If pos points to a low surrogate without a preceding high surrogate, it returns the code unit value.
- Return type: Number (not BigInt).

4. CODE POINT VS CODE UNIT
- JavaScript strings are sequences of UTF-16 code units; codePointAt returns the Unicode code point that may require reading two code units for characters outside BMP (surrogate pair).

5. BEHAVIOUR ON SURROGATE PAIRS
- If code unit at pos is a high surrogate (0xD800–0xDBFF) and pos+1 is a low surrogate (0xDC00–0xDFFF), codePointAt returns the combined code point: ((high - 0xD800) << 10) + (low - 0xDC00) + 0x10000.
- Otherwise returns the code unit value at pos.

6. USAGE PATTERNS
- Iterate over code points: for (let i=0; i<str.length; i++) { let cp = str.codePointAt(i); if (cp > 0xFFFF) i++; /* skip low surrogate */ }
- For clean iteration prefer for...of which iterates by code point (uses string iterator), or use Array.from(str) to split by code points.

7. EDGE CASES
- Not safe to assume one code unit per displayed character: emoji and many scripts use surrogate pairs or combining marks.
- Combining marks require grapheme cluster handling; codePointAt does not normalize or cluster-combine.

8. IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
- Engines implement codePointAt as a small mapper over UTF-16 code units with surrogate detection; performance characteristic: O(1) per call.

